1. What is Docker?
Docker is an open‑source containerization platform used to build, package, ship, and run applications in isolated environments called containers.
Docker ensures that an application runs consistently across different environments (development, testing, staging, production).

2. Why Docker is Used
Before Docker:

Application works on one machine but fails on another
Dependency and version conflicts
Heavy virtual machines
Slow deployments

With Docker:

Portable applications
Faster deployments
Consistent runtime environments
Efficient resource usage
Easy integration with CI/CD pipelines


3. Docker vs Virtual Machines
Docker containers:

Share the host OS kernel
Lightweight
Start in seconds
High performance

Virtual Machines:

Run their own OS
Heavy and slow
Consume more resources

Docker is not a VM.

4. Core Docker Components
Docker Engine
The core service that runs Docker containers.
Includes:

Docker Daemon
Docker CLI
REST API


Docker Image

A read‑only template
Built from Dockerfile
Contains application code and dependencies

Example:
nginx:latest
node:18


Docker Container

A running instance of a Docker image
Isolated from other containers
Can be started, stopped, deleted


Dockerfile

A text file with instructions to build an image
Acts as a blueprint


Docker Registry

Stores Docker images
Examples:

Docker Hub
AWS ECR
GCP Artifact Registry




5. Docker Architecture
User → Docker CLI → Docker Daemon → Images / Containers → Registry


6. Docker Lifecycle
Dockerfile → Image → Container → Running Application


7. Dockerfile Example (Node.js App)
FROM node:18
WORKDIR /app
COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm install
COPY . .
EXPOSE 3000
CMD ["npm", "start"]


8. Docker Basic Commands
Check Docker
docker --version
docker info


Image Commands
docker images
docker pull nginx
docker build -t app:latest .
docker rmi <image_id>


Container Commands
docker run app
docker run -d app
docker run -it app /bin/bash
docker run -p 3000:3000 app
docker ps
docker ps -a
docker stop <container_id>
docker start <container_id>
docker restart <container_id>
docker rm <container_id>


Logs & Debugging
docker logs <container_id>
docker exec -it <container_id> /bin/bash
docker inspect <container_id>


9. Environment Variables & Volumes
Environment Variables
docker run -e ENV=prod app
docker run --env-file .env app

Volumes
docker run -v /host/data:/container/data app


10. Docker Networking
Types:

bridge (default)
host
overlay (Kubernetes)

Commands:
docker network ls
docker network create app-network
docker run --network app-network app


11. Docker Registry Commands (Docker Hub)
docker login
docker tag app user/app:latest
docker push user/app:latest
docker pull user/app:latest
docker logout


12. Docker Cleanup Commands (Very Important)
docker system df
docker system prune
docker container prune
docker image prune
docker volume prune
docker stats


13. Docker Compose (Basics)
Used for multi‑container applications.
Commands:
docker-compose up -d
docker-compose down
docker-compose ps
docker-compose logs


14. Docker in CI/CD (Real Usage)
Typical pipeline steps:

Build image
Scan image
Push image
Deploy container

Example:
docker build -t myapp .
docker push myapp
docker run myapp

In Jenkins:
withDockerRegistry(credentialsId: 'docker-cred') {
  sh 'docker build -t user/app .'
  sh 'docker push user/app'
}


15. Docker + Kubernetes

Docker builds containers
Kubernetes manages containers

Docker handles:

Image creation
Container runtime

Kubernetes handles:

Scaling
Self‑healing
Load balancing
Rolling updates


16. Advantages of Docker

Portability
Scalability
Faster deployments
Easy rollback
Version control for environments
Strong DevOps support
